"Bef 1448":"vóór 1448","Fitche Castle, Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bocking, Essex, England":"Bocking, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England",", , , England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–Bef 1448":"–before 1448","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1374–1437":"1374–1437","–1448":"–1448","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","1325":"1325","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","Bef 1448":"before 1448","Fitche Castle, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Bocking, Essex, England":"Bocking, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England",", , , England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Worth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Worth, for example in Cheshire, Dorset, Sussex, and Kent, from Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The vocabulary word probably survived into the Middle English period in the sense of a subsidiary settlement dependent on a main village, and in some cases the surname may be a topographic name derived from this use. Compare   Worthy  .","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wort</i> ‘enclosure, elevated piece of land, farmstead’, or a habitational name from a place so named in northern Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Word","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Van der Woord</b>, a habitational name from any of the places called Woord or Woerd.","English: variant of   Worth  ."]},{"name":"Wortmann","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived on a raised, secure site, Middle Low German <i>wort</i> + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Worth   2."]},{"name":"Worthy","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>worthi</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>worthig</i>, <i>weorthig</i>, <i>wurthig</i>). The surname is probably habitational, from a place so named, such as Worthy (Hampshire, Devon) and Worthy Hill Farm (Wiltshire)."]},{"name":"Wurdeman","meanings":["Americanized form of North German <b>Wurdemann</b>, also <b>Würdemann</b>: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wurt</i> ‘farm area, field, woodland’. Compare   Worth  .","Americanized form of German <b>Würdemann</b>: from an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>wirdi</i> ‘dignity’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Wirth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Gunter, Dieter, Ernst, Gerhard, Manfred, Reinhold, Armin, Erna.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for an inn-keeper, Middle High German <i>wirt</i>, German <i>Wirt</i>.","German: status name for a man who was head of a family and master of his own household, from the same word in the sense ‘provider’."]}]},{"name":"Abram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, a variant of   Abraham .  It was probably originally a distinct name (meaning ‘high father’ in Hebrew). According to Genesis 17:5, the patriarch's name was changed by divine command from <i>Abram</i> to <i>Abraham</i>. From the Middle Ages, however, if not before, it was taken to be a contracted version."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Abram Worth had at least 1 daughter with Abram Worth. She died before 1448, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–Bef 1448":"–enne 1448","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1374–1437":"1374–1437","–1448":"–1448","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","1325":"1325","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","Bef 1448":"enne 1448","Fitche Castle, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bocking, Essex, England":"Bocking, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–Bef 1448":"–ennen vuotta 1448","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1374–1437":"1374–1437","–1448":"–1448","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","1325":"1325","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","Bef 1448":"ennen vuotta 1448","Fitc